Y COLLEGE, MS R.3.15 AND THE CIRCULATION OF CHAUCERIAN MANUSCRIPTS IN THE SIXTEENTH CENTURY -- tAFTERWORD: A PERSONAL TRIBUTE -- tLINNE R. MOONEY: LIST OF PUBLICATIONS -- tINDEX OF MANUSCRIPTS -- tGENERAL INDEX -- tTABULA GRATULATORIA0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays bringing out the richness and vibrancy of pre-modern textual culture in all its variety.Linne R. Mooney, Emeritus Professor of Palaeography at the University of York, has significantly advanced the study of later medieval English book production, particularly our knowledge of individual scribes; this collection honours her distinguished scholarship and responds to her wide-ranging research on Middle English manuscripts and texts. The thirteen essays brought together here take a variety of approaches - palaeographical, codicological, dialectal, textual, art historical - to the study of the English medieval book and to the varied environments (professional, administrative, mercantile, ecclesiastical) where manuscripts were produced and used during the period 1300-1550. Acknowledging that books and readers are no respecters of borders, this collection's geographical scope extends beyond England in the east to Ghent and Flanders, and in the west to Waterford and the Dublin Pale.Contributors explore manuscripts containing works by key writers, including Geoffrey Chaucer, John Gower, John Wyclif, and Walter Hilton. Major texts whose manuscript traditions are scrutinized include Speculum Vitae, the Scale of Perfection, the Canterbury Tales, and Confessio Amantis, along with a wide range of shorter works such as lyric poems, devotional texts, and historical chronicles. London book-making activities and the scribal cultures of other cities and monastic centres all receive attention, as does the book production of personal miscellanies. By considering both literary texts and the letters, charters, and writs that medieval scribes produced, in Latin and Anglo-French as well as English, this collection celebrates Professor Mooney's influence on the field and presents a holistic sense of England's pre-modern textual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Multiple languages.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aManuscripts, English (Middle)xHistory. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  a'Kings of England'.  aAdam Pinkhurst.  aEngland.  aFlanders.  aFrance.  aGeoffrey Chaucer, Canterbury Tales.  aGuildhall.  aHammond scribe.  aHiberno-English.  aIreland.  aJohn Carpenter.  aJohn Gower, Confessio Amantis.  aJohn Lydgate.  aJohn Marchaunt.  aJohn Shirley.  aJohn Stow.  aJohn Wyclif.  aLancastrian.  aLondon.  aMiddle English literature.  aPiers Plowman.  aRalph Strode.  aRipon.  aSpeculum Vitae.  aStephan Batman.  aWalter Hilton, Scale of Perfection.  aWilliam Caxton.  aWilliam Thynne.  aWynkyn de Worde.  abooks of hours.  achronicle.  aclerk.  acodicology.  acontinental manuscript production.  aediting.  afifteenth-century.  afourteenth-century.  ahandwriting.  aillumination.  amedieval book production.  amedieval literature.  amedieval manuscripts.  apalaeography.  apoetry.  aprose.  ascribes.  asecretary.  asixteenth-century.  averse.1 aConnolly, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Margaret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDriver, Martha W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFredell, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Daryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1